re, England, United Kingdom","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Osborne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Old English personal name composed of <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorn</i> ‘bear, warrior’ (both of Scandinavian origin). As a modern given name it generally represents a transferred use of the surname that was derived from this name during the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["From a Late Old English personal name composed of <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorn</i> ‘bear, warrior’ (both of Scandinavian origin). As a modern given name it generally represents a transferred use of the surname that was derived from this name during the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Osborne de Giffard II  Lord of Brimpsfield was born about 1044, in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Osbern Giffard d'Arques, Seigneur de Brimesfelde, was 60 and his mother, Havisia D'Arques, was 41. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Weva de Crepon. He died about 1096, in France, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1044–about 1096":"umbes 1044–umbes 1096","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1046–Female":"1046–Surnud","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1075–1142":"1075–1142","0985–1090":"0985–1090","1004–1080":"1004–1080","1080":"1080","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1090":"1090","about 1096":"umbes 1096","1044":"1044"